The start time and end time columns are converted to datetime data type.

In [3]:
df['age']=2019-df['member_birth_year']

Age column is created by subracting birth year from 2019 when the bike trips took place to make analysis better.

In [5]:
df['duration_min'] = df['duration_sec'] / 60

Duration in minutes column is also created by dividing duration in seconds by 60 for better analysis.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 fordgobike trips in the dataset with 16 columns; duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude ,end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip. Two columns were also created for better analysis; age and duration_min.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in showing how the trip duration is dependent on the other given attributes.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Trip duration is likely to be dependent on age, start stations, end stations, user_type, gender and bike_share.

Univariate Exploration¶

We start by looking at the distribution of the trip duration in minutes.¶

In [68]:
binsize = 10
bins = np.arange(0, df['duration_min'].max()+binsize, binsize)
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 6])
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'duration_min', bins = bins)
plt.xlabel('DURATION IN MIN')
plt.ylabel('TRIPS COUNT')
plt.xlim(-20,200)
plt.title('DURATION DISTRIBUTION IN MIN')
plt.show()

A long tail in the distribution makes it hard to see the distribution, so lets put it on log scale.

In [20]:
#Log transforming to better understand the data
plt.figure(figsize=[8,6])
bins = 10**np.arange(0 , 3 + 0.1 , 0.1)
ticks =  [ 1 , 3, 10, 30, 100, 300, 1000]
labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'duration_min' , bins = bins);
plt.xscale('log');
plt.xticks(ticks,labels);
plt.xlabel('DURATION IN MIN');
plt.title('DURATION DISTRIBUTION IN MIN');
plt.ylabel('TRIPS COUNT');

Most of the values fall between 2 minutes and 20 minutes. Most riders' trip duration was between 2 and 20 minutes while few riders' duration was below 2 minutes and above 20 minutes.

Average Bike Trip Duration The average bike lasts between 1 and just over 100 minutes with the majority of bike trips lasting just under 10 minutes.

#create the percent function
def percent(value):
    percent=round(df[value].value_counts()/len(df)*100)
    return percent
#returns a pie chart with percentages

Distribution of age¶

plt.ylabel('COUNT')
plt.show()

Most riders are between 20 years and 40 years.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration has a long tail due to large amount of values and one can not tell how age is distributed, I had to plot age distribution in log transform and found that the highest number of trips were made by riders aged between 20 years and 40 years and number of trips lessened as people grew older.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Birth year could not be used to plot age distribution, age column had to be created for better analysis by subtracting birth year from the current year(2022) and the trip duration was converted to minutes to understand the trip duration better by dividing duration_sec column by 60.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The trip duration depend mostly on age,user type and bike share, but it less likely depend on gender. The trip duration does not seem to depend on the start station id and end station id.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I also looked into relationship between gender and age, bike share and age & gender and user type. It showed that other gender are likely to be older people, older riders are not likely to share their bikes and subscribers are likely to be the most riders in all genders.

Multivariate Exploration¶

I want to explore in this part of the analysis is how a categorical variable is related to two qualitative variables.

How gender, trip duration and age are related.¶

In [15]:
plt.figure(figsize = [8, 6])
gender_markers = [['Male', 'o'],['Female', 's'],['Other', 'v']]
for gender, marker in gender_markers:
    df_gender = df[df['member_gender'] == gender]
    plt.scatter((df_gender['age']), df_gender['duration_min'], marker = marker, alpha=0.25)
plt.legend(['Male','Female','Other'])
plt.axis([10, 80, -5, 300 ])
plt.xlabel('AGE')
plt.ylabel('DURATION IN MIN')
plt.title('GENDER VS TRIP DURATION AND AGE')

The distribution is not clear enough.

I used facetgrid below for a clearer understanding.

In [16]:
genders = sb.FacetGrid(data = df, col = 'member_gender', col_wrap = 2, size = 5,xlim = [10, 80], ylim = [0, 250])
genders.map(plt.scatter, 'age', 'duration_min', alpha=0.25)
genders.set_xlabels('AGE')
genders.set_ylabels('DURATION IN MIN')
plt.show()

All these plots show that younger riders in all genders have longer trips compared to older people.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Males have the most number of longer trip durations but all younger riders in all genders are likely to have longest trips, younger riders both customers and subscribers are likely to have longer trips compared to older people even though subscribers had the most number of longer trip durations and younger riders who shared their bikes are likely to have longer trips compared to older people while the ones who did not share their bikes have almost the same trip duration distributed in all ages even though most riders did not share their bikes.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The Other gender plot shows that riders nearly 60 years have longer trip duration and Yes plot for bike share shows no much decrement which means riders who did not share their bikes have almost the same trip duration distributed in all ages which is suprising.

Exploration¶

The fordgobike dataset was downloaded and uploaded then loaded to jupyter notebook for exploration. The start time and end time columns are converted to datetime data type, age column is created by subracting birth year from 2022 to make analysis better and duration in minutes column is also created by dividing duration in seconds by 60 for better analysis. Univariate,bivariate and multivariate explorations were conducted and explained.

Conclusions¶

The trip duration depend mostly on age,user type and bike share, but it less likely depend on gender. Younger riders are most likely to have the longest trip duration.
